Business Case
1.0 Introduction/Background

2.0 Business Objective
As a start-up company, the goal of everyone within this organization is to produce the greatest product possible for a market segment that has been relatively untouched. While there is a plethora of attire-based applications in the mobile software market today, it is nearly impossible for current application leaders to tap into niche markets. The Outfittr software application development project aims to segment our way into this niche market of clothing enthusiasts that no other mobile software development company has tried before. We hope to use this untapped market to increase not only the reputation of this start-up company, but to also achieve market penetration and a financial foundation for the company.
3.0 Current Situation and Problem/Opportunity Statement
The world has become a complex and time-consuming place. Many individuals often spend too much time deciding what the proper attire for a particular situation will be so much time is wasted on indecision. Many of these problems stem from local weather conditions, vast or limited attire collections, and/or a lack of fashion sense. Therefore there is an untapped market for people who neither have the time nor competency to spend time researching various fashion norms and contribute to overall unhappiness related to lack of time towards attire planning. The Outfittr mobile software application aims to rectify this problem by incorporating already-existing data from different fashion repositories as well as location data in order to efficiently plan one’s attire for a given situation. Approaching the already-saturated market will require tapping into the niche fashion genres, such as Hipster, Punk Rock, etc. By using these niche markets, we hope to provide a ever-growing software solution in the long term.

mts.s: Here at Average Joe Designs, we are committed to designing the best apps for people that need them. Our goal is to help the those that are on the fringe of society, discover their style. With all the various social networks available, we discovered that there are huge communities of not just disenfranchised hipsters, but also of immigrants that have no avenue to find the styles they crave. We want to help them with not only finding those styles but also keeping them in line with either the up-to-date way to wear them or the proper way for their cultural standards. We not only want to help the community of Goth find that hot new must have black eyeliner, but also help the muslim woman to not only find a proper head dress, but also give her advice of what is considered the appropriate way to wear it. We want to design an app that caters to those that the mainstream fashion world shuns or ignores.

Our preliminary application development cost estimate is $70,067.  This cost reflects development cost of the most current IPhone and current IPad.  An additional cost not included in the estimate is the cost of doing business with Apple, which charges 30% for each sales transaction of the application. 
The estimate is not derived from direct quotes from developers, but from research of historical cost of development found via online.  Below is the breakdown of the estimate:

Cost for mobile application development varies depending on the complexity of the application.  In general, applications can be categorized as Simple; Database driven; Complex Database; and Enterprise.  Our application fits in the Complex Database category.
**Most Complex Database type application software take about sixteen weeks/four months to complete, but we’re aiming for 10 weeks.  To make sure we finish on time, we’re planning to use Agile Scrum method with its sprints and burndown chart to better determine if we can meet our deadline.**

The main features of the OutfitMe mobile application include the following:
Access to retail websites specializing in clothing and other fashion accessories. Retailers would be able to pay a small amount of money in order to promote their product in product recommendations.
Access to location information from each user of the application. Access to relevant weather information based on the location information collected from the user. The weather information will be used as a factor in determining the recommended clothing.
The application will be able to allow users to either search for existing clothing by use of bar codes, names, or branding, or by manually entering a generic type of clothing into the application’s database. Attributes will be associated with the different articles of clothing such as color, size, fit, etc.
Access to a mobile data connection from the user’s mobile wireless provider.
Access to a smart phone platform such as Android or iOS.
In-app purchases of recommended clothing or accessories the user does not explicitly state that he/she owns.
Other features suggested by users, if they add value to the mobile software application.
